<subSubSection id="909454EAFF49A49DFF75FF11FEC96BF5" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="D8310761FF49A49DFF75FF11FEC96BF5" blockId="131.[151,1437,151,898]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFF75FF11FE886BBD" bold="true" box="[199,335,151,177]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFDF2FF11FD096BBD" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[576,718,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFDF2FF11FD096BBD" box="[576,718,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Latin, from 
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFCD1FF11FC196BBD" box="[867,990,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">meridional</emphasis>
–for southern) was undoubtedly derived from Kusnezov collecting the 
<typeStatus id="0735B9C3FF49A49DFE5CFF3DFD826BD9" box="[494,581,187,213]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">syntype</typeStatus>
worker in 
<collectingRegion id="1A4AC983FF49A49DFD70FF3DFC6A6BD9" box="[706,941,187,213]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Santa Cruz Province</collectingRegion>
, which is second most southern province in 
<collectingCountry id="A09947F1FF49A49DFF25FF59FECD6BF5" box="[151,266,223,249]" name="Argentina" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Argentina</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="909454EAFF49A49DFF75FE84FB9669C1" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D8310761FF49A49DFF75FE84FB9669C1" blockId="131.[151,1437,151,898]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFF75FE84FE8B6A10" bold="true" box="[199,332,258,284]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Discussion.</emphasis>
The black head and mesosoma, dark ferruginous orange gaster, and lack of striae on the first gastral tergum separate 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFE31FEA1FDE96A4D" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[387,558,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFE31FEA1FDE96A4D" box="[387,558,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all congeners except 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFCDBFEA1FC3E6A4D" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1922" box="[873,1017,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pronotalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFCDBFEA1FC3E6A4D" box="[873,1017,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. pronotalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFB86FEA1FB1B6A4D" authorityName="Cuezzo &amp; Claver" authorityYear="2009" box="[1076,1244,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozanus">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFB86FEA1FB1B6A4D" box="[1076,1244,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. mendozanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFB5EFEA1FEE26A69" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFB5EFEA1FEE26A69" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Pogonomyrmex meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFE42FECDFD526A69" authorityName="Cuezzo &amp; Claver" authorityYear="2009" box="[496,661,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozanus">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFE42FECDFD526A69" box="[496,661,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. mendozanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on: (1) longitudinal rugae on cephalic dorsum irregular, widely spaced, and (2) medial rugae on mesonotum usually continue to pronotal collar. In 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFB84FEE9FB186A85" authorityName="Cuezzo &amp; Claver" authorityYear="2009" box="[1078,1247,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozanus">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFB84FEE9FB806A84" box="[1078,1095,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFBE7FEE9FB186A85" box="[1109,1247,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">mendozanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, (1) longitudinal rugae on cephalic dorsum regular, narrow, subparallel, and deeply incised, and (2) medial rugae on mesonotum diverge toward humeral shoulders of pronotum, often with one to few transverse rugae along anterior margin of pronotum. 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFEA1FE5DFD9F6AF9" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[275,600,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFEA1FE5DFD9F6AF9" box="[275,600,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Pogonomyrmex meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFC9BFE5DFC706AF9" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1922" box="[809,951,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pronotalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFC9BFE5DFC706AF9" box="[809,951,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. pronotalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on: (1) larger size (HW = 
<quantity id="1F76AA84FF49A49DFA9EFE5DFF006915" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.91" metricValueMax="2.06" metricValueMin="1.76" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" unit="mm" value="1.91" valueMax="2.06" valueMin="1.76">1.76–2.06 mm</quantity>
), (2) first gastral tergum moderately to strongly coriarious, dull to weakly shining anterad, (3) rugae on pronotum weak to moderately coarse, (4) medial rugae on mesonotum usually continue to anterior margin of pronotum, and (5) promesonotal suture usually weakly to moderately impressed; 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFC17FDC1FBF6696D" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1922" box="[933,1073,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pronotalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFC17FDC1FBF6696D" box="[933,1073,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. pronotalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is: (1) smaller (HW = 
<quantity id="1F76AA84FF49A49DFA9EFDC1FF006989" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.71" metricValueMax="1.81" metricValueMin="1.61" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" unit="mm" value="1.71" valueMax="1.81" valueMin="1.61">1.61–1.81 mm</quantity>
), (2) first gastral tergum weakly coriarious, weakly shining to smooth and strongly shining, (3) rugae on pronotum coarse, (4) medial rugae on mesonotum diverge or become transverse to rugoreticulate on pronotum but do not continue to anterior margin of pronotum, and (5) promesonotal suture usually absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="909454EAFF49A49DFF75FD50FCB6688E" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="D8310761FF49A49DFF75FD50FCB6688E" blockId="131.[151,1437,151,898]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFF75FD50FEE069FC" bold="true" box="[199,295,726,752]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Biology.</emphasis>
Little is known about the biology of 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFD75FD51FCB769FD" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[711,880,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFD75FD51FCB769FD" box="[711,880,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">P. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
other than that workers are solitary foragers. Partial nest excavations indicated that colonies probably contain about 500– 
<specimenCount id="CE88CCE8FF49A49DFC77FD7CFB946819" box="[965,1107,762,789]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="worker">700 workers</specimenCount>
. The two nests located by the author were in sandy-gravelly soil and had a tumulus that was 
<quantity id="1F76AA84FF49A49DFCE4FC98FC026835" box="[854,965,798,825]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" unit="cm" value="12.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="10.0">10–15 cm</quantity>
in diameter. 
<taxonomicName id="1F8E7CE2FF49A49DFBEAFC99FA5A6835" authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[1112,1437,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFBEAFC99FA5A6835" box="[1112,1437,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Pogonomyrmex meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be a lowland species that inhabits elevations from 
<quantity id="1F76AA84FF49A49DFCEEFCC4FC266851" box="[860,993,834,861]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.625" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="3.85" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" unit="m" value="462.5" valueMax="540.0" valueMin="385.0">
385– 
<specimenCount id="CE88CCE8FF49A49DFC26FCC4FC266851" box="[916,993,834,861]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="generic">540 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. This species occurs in the Patagonian steppe ecoregion, as defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="BC1F7A90FF49A49DFE4CFCE1FD15688D" author="Olson, D. M. &amp; Dinerstein, E. &amp; Wikramanayake, E. D. &amp; Burgess, N. D. &amp; Powell, G. V. N. &amp; Underwood, E. C. &amp; D'Amico, J. A. &amp; Itoua, I. &amp; Strand, H. E. &amp; Morrison, J. C. &amp; Loucks, C. J. &amp; Allnutt, T. F. &amp; Ricketts, T. H. &amp; Kura, Y. &amp; Lamoreux, J. F. &amp; Wettengel, W. W. &amp; Hedao, P. &amp; Kassem, K. R." box="[510,722,871,897]" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" pagination="933 - 938" refId="ref148173" refString="Olson, D. M., Dinerstein, E., Wikramanayake, E. D., Burgess, N. D., Powell, G. V. N., Underwood, E. C., D'Amico, J. A., Itoua, I., Strand, H. E., Morrison, J. C., Loucks, C. J., Allnutt, T. F., Ricketts, T. H., Kura, Y., Lamoreux, J. F., Wettengel, W. W., Hedao, P. &amp; Kassem, K. R. (2001) Terrestrial ecoregions of the world: a new map of life on Earth. Bioscience, 51 (11), 933 - 938. https: // doi. org / 10.1641 / 0006 - 3568 (2001) 051 [0933: TEOTWA] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2001">
Olson 
<emphasis id="EAFADB73FF49A49DFDFAFCE1FDBE688D" box="[584,633,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">et al</emphasis>
. (2001)
</bibRefCitation>
(
